There was plenty of lamb in the curry - they didn't skimp.  Delivery was quick, and the temperature was still very hot when I received it.  There was nothing to complain about about my order.  If you haven't eaten here you are wrong.  Keep up the great work!!!

Never. Again.  First ordered samosas- came out cold in the middle on a plate with a few iceberg lettuces and piece of tomato.  The owner (?) took it back and returned with a new order of samosas on the same sad pieces of lettuce with the same piece of tomato. They were extra microwaved and chewy, but at least warm in the middle the second time.  Then my vegetable jalfrezi had this long, skinny piece (maybe 3-4 inches) of PLASTIC in it. He was barely apologetic and didn’t share the same level of disgust and shock that I had. (Maybe he’s used to this happening a lot).  Rice was cold, naan didn’t seem hot and fresh. However, he did not charge us my meal on the bill because of the plastic, which- quite honestly is the least you can do as a business owner.  Because of the taste and quality of the food, I believe this restaurant uses prepacked food and then just reheats it and acts like it’s their own. Also, the place has no music going and dim flourescent lights, you can hear the kitchen and it just felt icky and creepy. The only way this business survives is their lunch buffet which is likely enjoyed by those who don’t care about food quality, but just want a cheap lunch where they can load up. Don’t support this business. It’s clear the owners do not care about their establishment or customers.  Now, I’m just hoping to not get sick from the food I had here.

In the mood for Indian food? This is the place to go! They're great because they ask your spice tolerance every time, regardless if you've been there before. If you're accustomed to spice I think the 8 or 9 with curries would be pretty spicy. If you're looking for a very mild spice 5 or 6 is a good place to start. I highly recommend getting naan(bread) with any sort of curry dish from here and dipping it in said curry. I usually go with the onion kulcha or the garlic naan. Sidenote: The rice refills are free. Sharing dishes here is also easy to do here, in case you want to try someone else's.

We arrived at the dimly lit restaurant for a late lunch at 2:15 unaware that they were closing in 15 minutes.  India Cafe's hours are not posted on the window.  We were told that we could go ahead and start at the buffet and were not warned that they would be closing in 15 minutes.  The waiter did not ask what we wanted to drink.  While we were in the middle of our first plate, we were told that they were closing the buffet and we should get any last food items from it before they took it all down.  This was yet another chance that the waiter could have told us that they closed at 2:30, at this point it was probably around 2:40.  At 2:51 the waiter came by and told us that we had to go because they were closed at 2:30.  I will chalk the waiter's rudeness up to not having a firm grip on the English language, but the fact that he repeatedly neglected to inform us that they would be closing soon was downright insipid.  Had he warned us that they were closing soon, he could have avoided later treating his paying patrons so rudely.  When asked how everything was, my friend explained how rude it was to be kicked out after not being warned of their impending closing, to which the waiter responded with silence.  The spinach pakora was so dry and hard that I was afraid of breaking my teeth on it.  Of the two chicken dishes I had, I found myself picking bones and bone chunks out of every other bite.  The tandoori chicken was beyond dry and bland.  From my sampling of the food, the recipes are uninspired and flavorless slop.  Needless to say we will never set foot in India Cafe, and I personally feel sorry for anyone who thinks their service or food is fit for dogs, let alone humans.
